What is Playwright, and why would you choose Playwright over Selenium in your project?

â€œPlaywright is an open-source end-to-end test automation tool developed by Microsoft. Compared to Selenium, Playwright is faster and more reliable because it has built-in auto-wait mechanisms, which reduce flaky tests. It supports cross-browser testing for Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit using a single API. We can also perform API testing using Playwrightâ€™s request context. Parallel execution is supported out of the box through Playwright Test, which helps reduce execution time in CI pipelines.â€

How does Playwright handle auto-waiting, and why is it better than using explicit waits in Selenium?

â€œPlaywright has built-in auto-waiting. Before performing any action like click or type, it automatically waits for the element to be present in the DOM, visible, enabled, and stable. Because of this, we usually donâ€™t need to write explicit waits, which helps reduce flaky tests. In Selenium, we often depend on explicit or implicit waits, whereas Playwright handles this internally. If needed for special cases, Playwright still provides methods like waitForSelector() or waiting for network events.â€

How do you handle parallel execution in Playwright, and how does it work internally?

â€œPlaywright supports parallel execution using workers. We configure the number of workers in the playwright.config file. Each worker runs tests in a separate browser context, which ensures test isolation and avoids shared state issues. By default, Playwright automatically decides the number of workers based on CPU cores, and in CI we usually limit the worker count for stability. This parallel execution significantly reduces execution time.â€

â€œI integrate Playwright with Jenkins by configuring a Jenkins pipeline job. In the pipeline, I install dependencies, install Playwright browsers, and execute tests using npm commands like npx playwright test. I configure environment variables and control parallel execution using the Playwright config. After execution, I publish Playwright HTML or Allure reports in Jenkins. This setup allows tests to run automatically on every build or pull request.â€

